A004001.name: Hofstadter-Conway $10000 sequence: a(n) = a(a(n-1)) + a(n-a(n-1)) with a(1) = a(2) = 1.
formula: Lim_{n->infinity} a(n)/n = 1/2 and as special cases, if n > 0, a(2^n-i) = 2^(n-1) for 0 <= i < = n-1; a(2^n+1) = 2^(n-1) + 1. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Aug 04 2002 [Corrected by _Altug Alkan_, Apr 03 2017]

A004002.name: Benford numbers: a(n)=e^e^...^e (n times) rounded to nearest integer.
formula: a(n) = round(e^e^...^e), where e occurs n times, a(0) = 1 (= e^0). - _Melissa O'Neill_, Jul 04 2015

A004003.name: Number of domino tilings (or dimer coverings) of a 2n X 2n square.
formula: a(n)^2 = Resultant(U(2*n,x/2), U(2*n,i*x/2)), where U(n,x) is a Chebyshev polynomial of the second kind and i = sqrt(-1). - _Seiichi Manyama_, Apr 13 2020
a(n) ~ 2 * (sqrt(2)-1)^(2*n+1) * exp(G*(2*n+1)^2/Pi), where G is the Catalan's constant A006752. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Dec 30 2020

A004006.name: a(n) = C(n,1) + C(n,2) + C(n,3), or n*(n^2 + 5)/6.
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) + n^2/2 - n/2 + 1, with a(0)=0. - _Paolo P. Lava_, Apr 12 2007
Euler transform of length 6 sequence [3, 1, 1, 0, 0, -1]. - _Michael Somos_, May 04 2007
Starting (1, 3, 7, 14, ...) = binomial transform of [1, 2, 2, 1, 0, 0, 0, ...]. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Apr 24 2008
a(n) = 2*a(n-1) + (n-1) - a(n-2) with a(0) = 0, a(1) = 1. - _Richard R. Forberg_, Jan 23 2014
a(n) = Sum_{i=1..n} binomial(n-2i,2). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Nov 18 2017
a(n) = n + Sum_{k=0..n} k*(n-k). - _Gionata Neri_, May 19 2018
G.f.: g(f(x)), where g is g.f. of A001477 and f is g.f. of A128834. - _Oboifeng Dira_, Jun 21 2020

A004007.name: Theta series of E_6 lattice.
formula: Expansion of eta(q)^9 / eta(q^3)^3 + 81*q * eta(q^3)^9 / eta(q)^3 in powers of q.
Expansion of a(q)^3 + 2*c(q)^3 in powers of q where a(), c() are cubic AGM theta functions. - _Michael Somos_, Oct 24 2006

A004008.name: Expansion of theta series of E_7 lattice in powers of q^2.
formula: Expansion of phi(q)^3 * (phi(q)^4 + 7 * 16 * q * psi(q^2)^4) in powers of q where phi(), psi() are Ramanujan theta functions. - _Michael Somos_, Oct 24 2006
G.f. is a period 1 Fourier series which satisfies f(-1 / (4 t)) = 2^(1/2) (t / i)^(7/2) g(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t) and g() is the g.f. for A003781. - _Michael Somos_, Aug 27 2013
Convolution of A005875 and A228746. - _Michael Somos_, Apr 21 2015

A004009.name: Expansion of Eisenstein series E_4(q) (alternate convention E_2(q)); theta series of E_8 lattice.
formula: Can also be expressed as E4(q) = 1 + 240 sum_{i=1}^infinity i^3 q^i/(1-q^i) - _Gene Ward Smith_, Aug 22 2006
Theta series of E_8 lattice = 1 + 240 * Sum ( sigma_3 (m) * q^2m ), m = 1..inf, where sigma_3 (m) is the sum of the cubes of the divisors of m (A001158).
Expansion of (phi(-q)^8 - (2 * phi(-q) * phi(q))^4 + 16 * phi(q)^8) in powers of q where phi() is a Ramanujan theta function.
Expansion of (eta(q)^24 + 256 * eta(q^2)^24) / (eta(q) * eta(q^2))^8 in powers of q. - _Michael Somos_, Dec 30 2008
G.f. A(x) satisfies 0 = f(A(x), A(x^2), A(x^4)) where f(u, v, w) = u^2 + 33*v^2 + 256*w^2 - 18*u*v + 16*u*w - 288*v*w . - _Michael Somos_, Jan 05 2006
G.f. is a period 1 Fourier series which satisfies f(-1 / t) = (t/i)^4 * f(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t). - _Michael Somos_, Dec 30 2008
Convolution square is A008410. A008411 is convolution of this sequence with A008410.
Expansion of Ramanujan's function Q(q^2) = 12 (omega/Pi)^4 g2 (Weierstrass invariant) in powers of q^2.
Expansion of a(q) * (a(q)^3 + 8*c(q)^3) in powers of q where a(), c() are cubic AGM theta functions. - _Michael Somos_, Jan 14 2015

A004010.name: Theta series of 12-dimensional Coxeter-Todd lattice K_12.
formula: G.f. is a period 1 Fourier series which satisfies f(-1 / (3 t)) = 27 (t/i)^6 f(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t). - _Michael Somos_, Dec 20 2015
G.f.: (3*a(x)^6 - 4*a(x)^3*b(x)^3 + 4*b(x)^6) / 3 where a(), b() are cubic AGM theta functions. - _Michael Somos_, Dec 25 2015

A004011.name: Theta series of D_4 lattice; Fourier coefficients of Eisenstein series E_{gamma,2}.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{a, b, c, d in Z} x^(a^2 + b^2 + c^2 + d^2 + a*d + b*d + c*d). - _Michael Somos_, Jan 11 2011
Expansion of (1 + k^2) * K(k^2)^2 / (Pi/2)^2 in powers of nome q. - _Michael Somos_, Jun 10 2006
Expansion of (1 - k^2/2) * K(k^2)^2 / (Pi/2)^2 in powers of nome q^2. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 14 2012
Expansion of b(x) * b(x^2) + 3 * c(x) * c(x^2) in powers of x where b(), c() are cubic AGM theta functions. - _Michael Somos_, Jan 11 2011
Expansion of b(x) * b(x^2) + c(x) * c(x^2) / 3 in powers of x^3 where b(), c() are cubic AGM theta functions. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 14 2012
G.f. is a period 1 Fourier series which satisfies f(-1 / (2 t)) = 2 (t/i)^2 f(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t). - _Michael Somos_, Sep 11 2007
G.f. A(x) satisfies 0 = f(A(x), A(x^2), A(x^4)) where f(u, v, w) = u^2 - 2*u*v - 7*v^2 - 8*v*w + 16*w^2. - _Michael Somos_, May 29 2005
Convolution square is A008658. - _Michael Somos_, Aug 21 2014
Expansion of 2*P(x^2) - P(x) in powers of x where P() is a Ramanujan Eisenstein series. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 16 2015
a(n) = number of Hurwitz quaternions of norm n. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 16 2015

A004012.name: Theta series of hexagonal close-packing.
formula: Expansion of a(x^3) * phi(x^8) + 2*x^2 * c(x^3) * psi(x^16) in powers of x where a(), c() are cubic AGM theta functions and phi(), psi() are Ramanujan theta functions.
a(n) is the number of integer solutions [i, j, k] to n = 2*i^2 + (j^2 + j*k + k^2) / 3 where j, k == mod(i, 2) (mod 3). - _Michael Somos_, Jul 19 2014

A004013.name: Theta series of body-centered cubic (b.c.c.) lattice.
formula: subs(q=q^2, ph)^3+(2*sqrt(q))^3*subs(q=q^4, ps)^3, where ps = A010054 = Sum_{k=0..infinity} q^(k*(k+1)/2), ph = A000122 = Sum_{k=-infinity, infinity} q^(k^2).
Expansion of phi(q^4)^3 + 8 * q^3 * psi(q^8)^3 in powers of q where phi(), psi() are Ramanujan theta functions. - _Michael Somos_, Oct 25 2006
Expansion of theta_3(q)^3 + theta_2(q)^3 in powers of q^(1/4).
G.f. is a period 1 Fourier series which satisfies f(-1 / (8 t)) = 2 (t/i)^(3/2) g(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t) and g() is the g.f. for A004015.

A004014.name: Norms of vectors in the b.c.c. lattice.

A004015.name: Theta series of face-centered cubic (f.c.c.) lattice.
formula: Expansion of phi(q^2)^3 + 12 * q * phi(q^2) * psi(q^4)^2 in powers of q where phi(), psi() are Ramanujan theta functions. - _Michael Somos_, Oct 25 2006
Expansion of (phi(q)^3 + phi(-q)^3) / 2 in powers of q^2 where phi() is a Ramanujan theta function. - _Michael Somos_, Oct 25 2006
Expansion of b(q) * phi(q^18) + c(q^3) * phi(q^2) in powers of q^3 where b(), c() are cubic AGM theta functions and phi() is a Ramanujan theta function. - _Michael Somos_, Oct 25 2006
Expansion of (theta_3(q)^3 + theta_4(q)^3) / 2 in powers of q^2.
G.f. is a period 1 Fourier series which satisfies f(-1 / (8 t)) = 2^(7/2) (t/i)^(3/2) g(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t) and g() is the g.f. for A004013.
G.f.: Sum_{i, j, k in Z} x^( i*i + j*j + k*k + i*j + i*k + j*k ). - _Michael Somos_, Jan 02 2012
Number of integer solutions to x^2 + y^2 + z^2 + x*y + x*z + y*z = n.
Number of integer solutions to x + y + z even and x^2 + y^2 + z^2 = 2 * n.
Number of integer solutions to x + y + z + w = 0 and x^2 + y^2 + z^2 + w^2 = 2 * n. (End)

A004016.name: Theta series of planar hexagonal lattice A_2.
formula: Expansion of a(q) in powers of q where a(q) is the first cubic AGM theta function.
Expansion of theta_3(q) * theta_3(q^3) + theta_2(q) * theta_2(q^3) in powers of q.
Expansion of phi(x) * phi(x^3) + 4 * x * psi(x^2) * psi(x^6) in powers of x where phi(), psi() are Ramanujan theta functions.
Expansion of (1 / Pi) integral_{0 .. Pi/2} theta_3(z, q)^3 + theta_4(z, q)^3 dz in powers of q^2. - _Michael Somos_, Jan 01 2012
Expansion of coefficient of x^0 in f(x * q, q / x)^3 in powers of q^2 where f(,) is Ramanujan's general theta function. - _Michael Somos_, Jan 01 2012
G.f. A(x) satisfies 0 = f(A(x), A(x^2), A(x^4)) where f(u, v, w) = u^2 - 3*v^2 - 2*u*w + 4*w^2. - _Michael Somos_, Jun 11 2004
G.f. A(x) satisfies 0 = f(A(x), A(x^2), A(x^3), A(x^6)) where f(u1, u2, u3, u6) = (u1-u3) * (u3-u6) - (u2-u6)^2. - _Michael Somos_, May 20 2005
G.f. is a period 1 Fourier series which satisfies f(-1 / (3 t)) = 3^(1/2) (t/i) f(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t). - _Michael Somos_, Sep 11 2007
G.f. A(x) satisfies A(x) + A(-x) = 2 * A(x^4), from Ramanujan.
G.f.: 1 + 6 * Sum_{k>0} x^k / (1 + x^k + x^(2*k)). - _Michael Somos_, Oct 06 2003
G.f.: sum( q^(n^2+n*m+m^2) ) where the sum (for n and m) extends over the integers. - _Joerg Arndt_, Jul 20 2011
G.f.: theta_3(q) * theta_3(q^3) + theta_2(q) * theta_2(q^3) = (eta(q^(1/3))^3 + 3 * eta(q^3)^3) / eta(q).
Euler transform of A192733. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 12 2012

A004017.name: Theta series of E_8 lattice with respect to deep hole.

A004018.name: Theta series of square lattice (or number of ways of writing n as a sum of 2 squares). Often denoted by r(n) or r_2(n).
formula: Factor n as n = p1^a1 * p2^a2 * ... * q1^b1 * q2^b2 * ... * 2^c, where the p's are primes == 1 (mod 4) and the q's are primes == 3 (mod 4). Then a(n) = 0 if any b is odd, otherwise a(n) = 4*(1 + a1)*(1 + a2)*...
G.f. = s(2)^10/(s(1)^4*s(4)^4), where s(k) := subs(q=q^k, eta(q)) and eta(q) is Dedekind's function, cf. A010815. [Fine]
Expansion of eta(q^2)^10 / (eta(q) * eta(q^4))^4 in powers of q. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 19 2004
Expansion of ( phi(q)^2 + phi(-q)^2 ) / 2 in powers of q^2 where phi() is a Ramanujan theta function.
G.f. A(x) satisfies 0 = f(A(x), A(x^2), A(x^4)) where f(u, v, w) = (u - v)^2 - (v - w) * 4 * w. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 19 2004
Euler transform of period 4 sequence [4, -6, 4, -2, ...]. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 19 2004
Moebius transform is period 4 sequence [4, 0, -4, 0, ...]. - _Michael Somos_, Sep 17 2007
G.f. is a period 1 Fourier series which satisfies f(-1 / (4 t)) = 2 (t/i) f(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t).
The constant sqrt(Pi)/GAMMA(3/4)^2 produces the first 324 terms of the sequence when expanded in base exp(Pi), 450 digits of the constant are necessary. - _Simon Plouffe_, Mar 03 2011

Let s = 16*q*(E1*E4^2/E2^3)^8 where Ek = Product_{n>=1} (1-q^(k*n)) (s=k^2 where k is elliptic k), then the g.f. is hypergeom([+1/2, +1/2], [+1], s) (expansion of 2/Pi*ellipticK(k) in powers of q).  - _Joerg Arndt_, Aug 15 2011
Dirichlet g.f. Sum_{n>=1} a(n)/n^s = 4*zeta(s)*L_(-4)(s), where L is the D.g.f. of the (shifted) A056594. [Raman. J. 7 (2003) 95-127]. - _R. J. Mathar_, Jul 02 2012

A Jacobi identity: theta_3(0, q)^2 = 1 + 4*Sum_{r>=0} (-1)^r*q^(2*r+1)/(1 - q^(2*r+1)). See, e.g., the Grosswald reference (p. 15, p. 116, but p. 32, Lemma 2 with the proof, has the typo r >= 1 instead of r >= 0 in the sum, also in the proof). See the link with the Jacobi-Legendre letter.

Identity used by Weierstraß (see the König-Sprekels book, p. 187, eq. (5.12) and p. 281, with references, but there F(x) from (5.11) on p. 186 should start with nu =1 not 0):  theta_3(0, q)^2 = 1 + 4*Sum_{n>=1} q^n/(1 + q^(2*n)). Proof: similar to the one of the preceding Jacobi identity. (End)

G.f.: Theta_3(q)^2 = hypergeometric([1/2, 1/2],[1],lambda(q)), with lambda(q) = Sum_{j>=1} A115977(j)*q^j. See the Kontsevich and Zagier link, with Theta -> Theta_3, z -> 2*z and q -> q^2. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, May 27 2018

A004019.name: a(0) = 0; for n > 0, a(n) = (a(n-1) + 1)^2.
formula: It follows from Aho and Sloane that there is a constant c such that a(n) is the nearest integer to c^(2^n). In fact a(n+1) = nearest integer to b^(2^n) - 1 where b = 2.25851845058946539883779624006373187243427469718511465966.... - _Henry Bottomley_, Aug 30 2005

A004020.name: Theta series of square lattice with respect to edge.
formula: Expansion of q^(-1/2) * c(q) / 2 in powers of q^2 where c(q) is the third function in the quadratic Gauss AGM. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 10 2006
Expansion of 2 * phi(x) * psi(x^2) in powers of q where phi(), psi() are Ramanujan theta functions. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 10 2006

A004023.name: Indices of prime repunits: numbers n such that 11...111 (with n 1's) = (10^n - 1)/9 is prime.

A004024.name: Theta series of b.c.c. lattice with respect to deep hole.
formula: 4*eta(32z)^4/eta(8z) = 4*Sum q^(x^2+2y^2+2z^2), x, y, z >= 1 and odd.

A004025.name: Theta series of b.c.c. lattice with respect to long edge.
formula: Expansion of 2 * x * phi(x) * psi(x^4)^2 = 2 * x * psi(-x^2)^4 / phi(-x) in powers of x where phi(), psi() are Ramanujan theta functions.
Expansion of 2 * eta(q^2)^5 * eta(q^8)^4 / (eta(q)^2 * eta(q^4)^4) in powers of q.

A004026.name: Number of perfect quadratic forms or lattices in dimension n.

A004027.name: Number of arithmetic n-dimensional crystal classes.

A004028.name: Number of geometric n-dimensional crystal classes.

A004033.name: Theta series of lattice A_2 tensor E_8 (dimension 16, det. 6561, min. norm 4). Also theta series of Eisenstein version of E_8 lattice.
formula: Theta series is x^8-48*x^2*y, x = phi_0(z) (see A004016), y = Delta_12(z) (see A007332) in the notation of SPLAG, Chap. 4. See A037150 for Maple code.
Expansion of a(x)^2 * (a(x)^6 - 48*x * f(-x)^6 * f(-x^3)^6) in powers of x where a() is a cubic AGM theta function and f() is a Ramanujan theta function. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 01 2017
G.f. is a period 1 Fourier series which satisfies f(-1 / (3 t)) = 81 (t/i)^8 f(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t). - _Michael Somos_, Feb 01 2017

A004034.name: Theta series of Leech lattice with respect to deep hole of type A_1.

A004036.name: The coding-theoretic function A(n,4,6) (the next term is at least 166).

A004040.name: Inversion of A000257.
formula: Invert: define b by 1+Sum a(n)x^n = 1/(1 - Sum b(n)x^n).

A004041.name: Scaled sums of odd reciprocals: a(n) = (2*n + 1)!!*(Sum_{k=0..n} 1/(2*k + 1)).
formula: a(n) is coefficient of x^(2*n+2) in (arctanh x)^2, multiplied by (n + 1)*(2*n + 1)!!.

a(n) = Sum_{i=k+1..n} (-1)^(k+1-i)*2^(n-1)*binomial(i-1, k)*s1(n, i) with k = 1, where s1(n, i) are unsigned Stirling numbers of the first kind. - Victor Adamchik (adamchik(AT)ux10.sp.cs.cmu.edu), Jan 23 2001
For n >= 1, a(n-1) = 2^(n-1)*n!*(Sum_{k=0..n-1} (-1)^k*binomial(1/2, k)/(n - k)). - _Milan Janjic_, Dec 14 2008

A004042.name: Periods of reciprocals of A006883, starting with first nonzero digit.

A004044.name: Size of minimal covering code in {Z_3}^n with covering radius 1.

A004045.name: Minimal size of binary code of length n such that every vector is within distance 1 of at least 2 codewords.

A004046.name: Theta series of extremal 3-modular even 24-dimensional lattice with minimal norm 6 and det = 3^12.
formula: Theta series = a^12 - 9/2*a^8*b^4 + 414*a^6*b^6 + 1458*a^4*b^8 + 1998*a^2*b^10 + 459/2*b^12 (see PARI code for details).
G.f.: (27*a(x)^12 - 72*a(x)^9*b(x)^3 + 64*a(x)^6*b(x)^6 + 16*a(x)^3*b(x)^9 - 8*b(x)^12) / 27 where a(), b() are cubic AGM theta functions, - _Michael Somos_, Dec 25 2015

A004048.name: Theta series of 14-dimensional extremal 3-modular lattice with det 3^7, minimal norm 4, group 2 X G_2(3).

A004050.name: Numbers of the form 2^j + 3^k, for j and k >= 0.

A004053.name: For m=2,3,..., write m in bases 2,3,..,m.

A004054.name: Expansion of (1-x)/((1+x)*(1-2*x)*(1-3*x)).
formula: The sequence 0, 0, 1, ... has a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} binomial(n, 2*k)*A001045(2*k).

The signed sequence 0, 1, -3, ... has g.f. x*(1+x)/((1-x)*(1+2*x)*(1+3*x)) and a(n) = 1/6 + (-2)^n/3 - (-3)^n/2. It is the third inverse binomial transform of A001045(2*n-1) - 0^n/2. - _Paul Barry_, Apr 21 2004

A004055.name: ((p-1)/2)! mod p for odd primes p.

A004059.name: a(n) gives position of first n in A057561.

A004061.name: Numbers n such that (5^n - 1)/4 is prime.

A004062.name: Numbers n such that (6^n - 1)/5 is prime.

A004063.name: Numbers n such that (7^n - 1)/6 is prime.

A004064.name: Numbers n such that (12^n - 1)/11 is prime.

A004065.name: Define predecessors of n, P(n), to consist of numbers whose binary representation is obtained from that of n by replacing 10 with 01 or changing a final 1 to a 0; then a(0)=1, a(n) = Sum a(P(n)), n>0.

A004066.name: Number of simple regular trivalent bicolored graphs with 2n nodes.

A004068.name: Number of atoms in a decahedron with n shells.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{i=0..n-1} A005891(i). - Xavier Acloque, Oct 08 2003

A004069.name: Numbers of points in nontrivial partial geometries.

A004070.name: Table of Whitney numbers W(n,k) read by antidiagonals, where W(n,k) is maximal number of pieces into which n-space is sliced by k hyperplanes, n >= 0, k >= 0.
formula: W(n, k) = Sum_{i=0..n} binomial(k, i). - _Bill Gosper_
W(n, k) = if k=0 or n=0 then 1 else W(n, k-1)+W(n-1, k-1). - _David Broadhurst_, Jan 05 2000
The table W(n,k) = A000012 * A007318(transform), where A000012 = (1; 1,1; 1,1,1;...). - _Gary W. Adamson_, Nov 15 2007
E.g.f. for row n: (1 + x + x^2/2! + ... + x^n/n!)* exp(x). - _Geoffrey Critzer_, Mar 15 2010
G.f.: 1 / (1 - x - x*y*(1 - x^2)) = Sum_{0 <= k <= n} x^n * y^k * T(n, k). - _Michael Somos_, May 31 2016

A004071.name: Start with a(0)=1; replace each i with 12...i, then add 1 to final digit.

A004072.name: Read the terms of A004071 backwards.

A004073.name: Start with a(1)=1; to get a(n) replace each i in a(n-1) with 12...i, then append n.

A004074.name: a(n) = 2*A004001(n) - n, where A004001 is the Hofstadter-Conway $10000 sequence.

A004075.name: Number of Skolem sequences of order n.
formula: For n>1, a(n)=A059106(n)*2 because A059106 ignores reflected solutions. - _Martin Fuller_, Mar 08 2007

A004076.name: Number of hooked Skolem sequences of order n.

A004077.name: Extended Skolem sequences of order n.

A004079.name: a(n) = maximal m such that an m X n Florentine rectangle exists.

A004080.name: Least k such that H(k) >= n, where H(k) is the harmonic number sum_{i=1..k} 1/i.
formula: The quotient of two successive terms of this sequence has exp(1) for limit. - _Sébastien Dumortier_, Jun 29 2005
a(n) = exp(n - gamma + o(1)). - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Mar 10 2009
a(n) = A002387(n) for n>1. - _Robert G. Wilson v_, Jun 18 2015

A004081.name: a(n) = n-th positive integer such that only one integer lies between exp(s(m)) and exp(s(m+1)), where s(m) = 1 + 1/2 + 1/3 + . . . + 1/m.
formula: Conjecturally, a(n) = floor(n/(2 - exp(g)) - 1/2 + exp(g)/(24n)), where g is the Euler-Mascheroni constant. - David W. Cantrell (DWCantrell(AT)sigmaxi.net), Aug 11 2007

A004082.name: Numbers k such that sin(k-1) <= 0 and sin(k) > 0.

A004083.name: Numbers k such that cos(k-1) <= 0 and cos(k) > 0.

A004084.name: a(n) = n-th positive integer k such that tan(k-1) <= 0 and tan(k) > 0.
formula: a(n) = ceiling(Pi*(n-1)) for n>1. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Feb 14 2004

A004085.name: Sum of digits of Euler totient function of n.

A004086.name: Read n backwards (referred to as R(n) in many sequences).
formula: a(n) = d(n,0) with d(n,r) = if n=0 then r, otherwise d(floor(n/10), r*10+(n mod 10)). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Mar 04 2010
a(10*n+x) = x*10^m + a(n) if 10^(m-1) <= n < 10^m and 0 <= x <= 9. - _Robert Israel_, Jun 11 2015

A004088.name: Sum of digits of number of partitions of n.

A004089.name: Reverse digits of number of partitions of n.

A004090.name: Sum of digits of Fibonacci numbers.

A004092.name: Sum of digits of even numbers.

A004095.name: Sum of digits of Catalan numbers.

A004097.name: Sum of digits of Bell numbers.

A004099.name: Sum of digits of Euler numbers.

A004100.name: Number of labeled nonseparable bipartite graphs on n nodes.

A004101.name: Number of partitions of n of the form a_1*b_1^2 + a_2*b_2^2 + ...; number of semi-simple rings with n elements.

A004102.name: Number of signed graphs with n nodes. Also number of 2-multigraphs on n nodes.
formula: Euler transform of A053465. - _Andrew Howroyd_, Sep 25 2018

A004103.name: Number of nets on n unlabeled nodes.

A004104.name: Number of self-dual signed graphs with n nodes. Also number of self-complementary 2-multigraphs on n nodes.

A004105.name: Number of point-self-dual nets with 2n nodes. Also number of directed 2-multigraphs with loops on n nodes.

A004106.name: Number of line-self-dual nets (or edge-self-dual nets) with n nodes.

A004107.name: Number of self-dual nets with 2n nodes.

A004108.name: Number of n-node unlabeled connected graphs without endpoints.
formula: Inverse Euler transform of A004110. - _Andrew Howroyd_, Sep 09 2018

A004109.name: Number of connected trivalent (or cubic) labeled graphs with 2n nodes.

A004110.name: Number of n-node unlabeled graphs without endpoints (i.e., no nodes of degree 1).

A004111.name: Number of rooted identity trees with n nodes (rooted trees whose automorphism group is the identity group).
formula: Recurrence: a(n+1) = (1/n) * sum_{k=1..n} ( sum_{d|k} (-1)^(k/d+1) d*a(d) ) * a(n-k+1). - Mitchell Harris, Dec 02 2004
G.f. satisfies A(x) = x exp(A(x)-A(x^2)/2+A(x^3)/3-A(x^4)/4+...) [Harary and Prins]
Also A(x) = Sum_{n >= 1} a(n)*x^n = x * Product_{n >= 1} (1+x^n)^a(n).

A004112.name: Numbers k where |cos(k)| (or |cosec(k)| or |cot(k)|) decreases monotonically to 0; also |tan(k)|, |sec(k)|, |sin(k)| increases.

A004113.name: Number of rooted trees with n nodes and 2-colored non-leaf nodes.
formula: Shifts left and halves under EULER transform.

A004114.name: Number of trees with n nodes and 2-colored internal (non-leaf) nodes.
formula: G.f.: 1+B(x)-x*B(x)-B(x)^2/2+B(x^2)/2 where B(x) is g.f. of A004113. - _Christian G. Bower_, Dec 15 1999

A004115.name: Number of unlabeled rooted nonseparable graphs with n nodes.

A004118.name: Maximal excess of a Hadamard matrix of order 4n.
formula: [x] denotes the integer part. (See Kounias and Farmakis, 1988.) (End)

A004119.name: a(0)=1; thereafter a(n) = 3*2^(n-1)+1.
formula: For n>3, a(3)=13, a(n)= a(n-1)+2*floor(a(n-1)/2). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Aug 14 2002
For n>=1, a(n) = A049775(n+1)/2^(n-2). For n>=2, a(n) = 2a(n-1)-1; see also A000051. - _Philippe Deléham_, Feb 20 2004

A004121.name: Generalized weak orders on n points.

A004122.name: Generalized weak orders on n points.

A004123.name: Number of generalized weak orders on n points.
formula: Stirling transform of A000165. - _Karol A. Penson_, Jan 25 2002
Recurrence: a(n) = 2*Sum_{k=1..n} binomial(n, k)*a(n-k), a(0)=1. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Mar 27 2003
G.f.: 1 + x*(G(0) - 1)/(x-1) where G(k) = 1 - (2*k+2)/(1-x-k*x)/(1-x/(x-1/G(k+1) )); (recursively defined continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jan 15 2013
a(n) = log(3/2)*Integral_{x>=0} floor(x)^n * (3/2)^(-x) dx. - _Peter Bala_, Feb 14 2015

A004124.name: Discriminant of n-th cyclotomic polynomial.
formula: Sign(a(n)) = (-1)^(phi(n)*(phi(n)-1)/2). Magnitude: For prime p, a(p) = p^(p-2). For n = p^e, a prime power, a(n) = p^(((p-1)*e-1)*p^(e-1)). For n = Product_{i=1..k} p_i^e_i, a product of prime powers, a(n) = Product_{i=1..k} a(p_i^e_i)^phi(n/p_i^e_i).

a(n) = Sign(a(n))*(n^phi(n))/(Product_{p|n, p prime} p^(phi(n)/(p-1))). See the Ribenboim reference, p. 297, eq.(1), with the sign taken from the previous formula and n=2 included. [_Wolfdieter Lang_, Aug 03 2011]

A004125.name: Sum of remainders of n mod k, for k = 1, 2, 3, ..., n.
formula: a(n) = n^2 - Sum_{k=1..n} sigma(k) = A000290(n) - A024916(n), hence asymptotically a(n) = n^2*(1-Pi^2/12) + O(n*log(n)^(2/3)). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Apr 28 2002. Asymptotics corrected/improved by _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Feb 22 2015
a(n) = Sum_{i=1..n} (n mod i). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Sep 15 2017

A004126.name: a(n) = n*(7*n^2 - 1)/6.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{i = n..2*n-1} A000217(i). - _Bruno Berselli_, Sep 06 2017
a(n) = n^3 + Sum_{k=0..n-1} k*(k+1)/2. Alternately, a(n) = A000578(n) + A000292(n-1) for n>0. - _Bruno Berselli_, May 23 2018

A004127.name: Number of planar hexagon trees with n hexagons.
formula: See Theorem 3 on p. 142 in the Beineke-Pippert paper; also the Maple and Mathematica codes here.

A004128.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} floor(3*n/3^k).
formula: a(n) = n + floor(n/3) + floor(n/9) + floor(n/27) + ... = n + a(floor(n/3)) = n + A054861(n) = A054861(3n) = (3*n - A053735(n))/2. - _Henry Bottomley_, May 01 2001
a(n) = Sum_{k>=0} floor(n/3^k). a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(log_3(n))} floor(n/3^k), n >= 1. - _Hieronymus Fischer_, Aug 14 2007
Recurrence: a(n) = n + a(floor(n/3)); a(3n) = 3*n + a(n); a(n*3^m) = 3*n*(3^m-1)/2 + a(n). - _Hieronymus Fischer_, Aug 14 2007
a(k*3^m) = k*(3^(m+1)-1)/2, 0 <= k < 3, m >= 0. - _Hieronymus Fischer_, Aug 14 2007
Asymptotic behavior: a(n) = (3/2)*n + O(log(n)), a(n+1) - a(n) = O(log(n)); this follows from the inequalities below. - _Hieronymus Fischer_, Aug 14 2007
a(n) <= (3n-1)/2; equality holds for powers of 3. - _Hieronymus Fischer_, Aug 14 2007
a(n) >= (3n-2)/2 - floor(log_3(n)); equality holds for n = 3^m - 1, m > 0. - _Hieronymus Fischer_, Aug 14 2007
Lim inf (3n/2 - a(n)) = 1/2, for n-->oo. - _Hieronymus Fischer_, Aug 14 2007
Lim sup (3n/2 - log_3(n) - a(n)) = 0, for n-->oo. - _Hieronymus Fischer_, Aug 14 2007
Lim sup (a(n+1) - a(n) - log_3(n)) = 1, for n-->oo. - _Hieronymus Fischer_, Aug 14 2007

A004129.name: Postage stamp problem: largest m such that there exists an n-subset S of nonnegative integers such that 1,...,m can be expressed as a sum of two distinct elements of S.
formula: The g.f. (z^4+z^3+2*z^2+2*z+1)*(z^2+z+1)/((z-1)*(z^5+z^4+z^3-z-1)) conjectured by _Simon Plouffe_ in his 1992 dissertation is wrong. - _Sean A. Irvine_, Nov 21 2015
At present no g.f. is known. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Jan 14 2021

A004130.name: Numerators in expansion of (1-x)^{-1/4}.
formula: a(n) = prod(k=1, n, (4k-3)/k * 2^A007814(k)), proved by _Mitch Harris_, following a conjecture by _Ralf Stephan_.
a(n) = 2^(e_2((2n)!)-n)/n! Product[4k+1,{k,0,n-1}], where e_2((2n)!) is the highest power of 2 that divides (2n)! (sequence A005187). - _Emanuele Munarini_, Jan 25 2011

A004131.name: Modular postage stamp problem: largest m such that there exists an n-subset S of nonnegative integers such that 0,...,m-1 can be expressed as a mod-m sum of two distinct elements of S.

A004133.name: Additive bases: a(n) is the least integer such that there is an n-element set of nonnegative integers, the sums of pairs (of distinct elements) of which are distinct and at most a(n).

A004134.name: Denominators in expansion of (1-x)^{-1/4} are 2^a(n).
formula: a(n) = 3*n - A000120(n). Recurrence: a(2n) = a(n) + 3n, a(2n+1) = a(n) + 3n + 2. Proved by _Mitch Harris_, following a conjecture by _Ralf Stephan_.

A004135.name: Additive bases: a(n) is the least integer k such that in the cyclic group Z_k there is a subset of n elements all pairs (of distinct elements) of which add up to a different sum (in Z_k).

A004136.name: Additive bases: a(n) is the least integer k such that in the cyclic group Z_k there is a subset of n elements all pairs (of not necessarily distinct elements) of which add up to a different sum (in Z_k).

A004137.name: Maximal number of edges in a graceful graph on n nodes.

A004138.name: From a counter moving problem.
formula: G.f. = -(-1+z**2-4*z**3+2*z**4)/((z-1)*(2*z**4-z**3+z**2+z-1)). [Conjectured (correctly) by _Simon Plouffe_ in his 1992 dissertation.]

A004140.name: Number of nonempty labeled simple graphs on nodes chosen from an n-set.
formula: E.g.f.: exp(x)*(A(x)-1), where A(x) is e.g.f. for A006125. - _Geoffrey Critzer_, Oct 09 2012

A004141.name: Norm of a matrix.
formula: The scanned page from Kammler and McGlinn (page 843 of the article) gives a fairly explicit way to calculate a(n). - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Jul 09 2015

A004144.name: Nonhypotenuse numbers (indices of positive squares that are not the sums of 2 distinct nonzero squares).

A004145.name: Number of degenerate simplices in n-cube.

A004146.name: Alternate Lucas numbers - 2.
formula: a(n) = 2*(T(n, 3/2)-1) with Chebyshev's polynomials T(n, x) of the first kind. See their coefficient triangle A053120.
a(n) = 2*T(n, 3/2) - 2, with twice the Chebyshev's polynomials of the first kind, 2*T(n, x=3/2) = A005248(n).
a(n) = b(n) + b(n-1), n>=1, with b(n):=A027941(n-1), n>=1, b(-1):=0, the partial sums of S(n, 3) = U(n, 3/2) = A001906(n+1), with S(n, x) = U(n, x/2) Chebyshev's polynomials of the second kind.
a(n) = b(n-1) + b(n-2), n>=1, with b(n):=A027941(n), b(-1):=0, partial sums of S(n, 3) = U(n, 3/2) = A001906(n+1), Chebyshev's polynomials of the second kind.
a(n) = n*Sum_{k=1..n} binomial(n+k-1,2*k-1)/k, n > 0. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Sep 03 2010
a(n) = floor(tau^(2*n)*(tau^(2*n) - floor(tau^(2*n)))), where tau = (1+sqrt(5))/2. - _L. Edson Jeffery_, Aug 26 2013
a(n) = U(n-1,sqrt(5)/2)^2, for n >= 1, where U(n,x) denotes the Chebyshev polynomial of the second kind.
a(n) = the bottom left entry of the 2 X 2 matrix T(n, M), where M is the 2 X 2 matrix [0, -3/2; 1, 5/2] and T(n,x) denotes the Chebyshev polynomial of the first kind.
See the remarks in A100047 for the general connection between Chebyshev polynomials of the first kind and 4th-order linear divisibility sequences. (End)
exp( Sum_{n >= 1} a(n)*x^n/n ) = 1 + Sum_{n >= 1} Fibonacci(2*n)*x^n. Cf. A001350. - _Peter Bala_, Mar 19 2015
E.g.f.: exp(phi^2*x) + exp(x/phi^2) - 2*exp(x), where phi = (1 + sqrt(5))/2. - _G. C. Greubel_, Aug 24 2015
a(n) = a(-n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Aug 27 2015

a(n)^3 = Lucas(6*n) - 5*Lucas(4*n) + 10*Lucas(2*n) - 10*Lucas(0*n) + 5*Lucas(-2*n) - Lucas(-4*n) and so on (follows from Binet's formula for Lucas(2*n) and the algebraic identity (x + 1/x - 2)^m = f(x) + f(1/x) where f(x) = (x - 1)^(2*m - 1)/x^(m-1) ). (End)
Lim_{n->infinity} a(n+1)/a(n) = (3 + sqrt(5))/2 = A104457. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jun 03 2016
a(n) = (phi^n - phi^(-n))^2, where phi = A001622 = (1 + sqrt(5))/2. - _Diego Rattaggi_, Jun 10 2020

A004147.name: Number of n-state Turing machines which halt.

A004148.name: Generalized Catalan numbers: a(n+1) = a(n) + Sum_{k=1..n-1} a(k)*a(n-1-k).
formula: G.f.: (1/z)*(1-C(-z/(1-3*z+z^2))), where C(z)=(1-sqrt(1-4*z))/(2*z) is the Catalan function. - _Emeric Deutsch_, Nov 19 2003
G.f.: 1 + F(x, x)/x, where F(x, t) is the g.f. of the Narayana numbers: xF^2 - (1-x-tx)F + tx = 0. - _Emeric Deutsch_, Nov 19 2003
G.f. A(x) satisfies the functional equation: x^2*A(x)^2 - (x^2 - x + 1)*A(x) + 1 = 0. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 20 2003
Series reversion of g.f. A(x) is -A(-x) (if offset 1). - _Michael Somos_, Jul 20 2003

a(n) = Sum_{k=ceiling((n+1)/2)..n} (binomial(k, n-k)*binomial(k, n-k+1)/k) for n >= 1. - _Emeric Deutsch_, Nov 12 2003 This formula counts (i) disjoint-diagonal dissections by number of diagonals, (ii) peak-less Motzkin paths by number of up steps, (iii) UUU- and DDD-free Dyck paths by number of ascents. - _David Callan_, Mar 23 2004
G.f.: (1/(1+x^2))*M(x/(1+x^2)), M(x) the g.f. of the Motzkin numbers A001006;
G.f.: 1 + x*exp( Sum_{n>=1} (x^n/n)*(Sum_{k=0..n} C(n,k)^2*x^k) ). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Mar 15 2011
G.f.: exp( Sum_{n>=1} A051292(n)*x^n/n ), where A051292(n) is a Whitney number of level n. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Mar 15 2011

Let the g.f. be A(x), then B(x)=(1+x*A(x)) = 1/(1-z/(1-z/(1-z/(...)))) where z=x/(1+x+x^2), B(x) = 1 +1*x + 1*x^2 +1*x^3 + 2*x^4 + 4*x^5 + ... is the g.f. of this sequence prepended with 1; more generally B(x) = C(x/(1+x+x^2)) where C(x) is the g.f. for the Catalan numbers (A000108). - _Joerg Arndt_, Mar 18 2011

D-finite with recurrence: (n+2)*a(n) - (2n+1)*a(n-1) + (1-n)*a(n-2) + (5-2n)*a(n-3) + (n-4)*a(n-4) = 0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Dec 01 2011. This recurrence follows from the Wilf-Zeilberger (WZ) proof technique applied to Sum_{k=ceiling((n+1)/2)..n} (binomial(k,n-k) * binomial(k,n-k+1)/k). - _T. Amdeberhan_, Jul 23 2012
Given g.f. A(x), then B(x) = x * A(x) satisfies B(x) = x + x*B(x) / (1 - x*B(x)). - _Michael Somos_, Jun 05 2014

A004149.name: Generalized Catalan numbers: a(n+1) = a(n) + Sum_{k=2..n-1} a(k)a(n-1-k).

A004151.name: Omit trailing zeros from n.
formula: a(n) = a(n/10) if n mod 10 = 0, otherwise n. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Feb 02 2012
G.f. A(x) satisfies: A(x) = A(x^10) + x/(1 - x)^2 - 10*x^10/(1 - x^10)^2. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Oct 27 2019

A004152.name: Sum of digits of n!.
formula: Luca shows that a(n) >> log n. In particular, a(n) > log_10 n - log_10 log_10 n. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Dec 27 2011
Sanna improved Luca's result to a(n) >> log n log log log n. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Jan 30 2015

A004154.name: Omit trailing zeros from factorial numbers.
formula: a(n+1) = A004151((n+1)*a(n)). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Nov 24 2012, corrected by _M. F. Hasler_, Oct 16 2014

A004155.name: Sum of digits of n-th odd number.

A004157.name: Sum of digits of n-th triangular number.

A004159.name: Sum of digits of n^2.
formula: a(10n) = a(n). If n > 1 is not a multiple of 10, then a(n)=4 iff n = 10^k+1 = A062397(k), a(n)=7 iff n is in A215614={4, 5, 32, 49, 149, 1049}, and else a(n) >= 9. - _M. F. Hasler_, Sep 23 2014

A004160.name: Sum of digits of tetrahedral numbers.

A004162.name: Sum of digits of pentagonal numbers.

A004169.name: Values of n for which a regular polygon with n sides cannot be constructed with ruler and compass.
formula: a(n) = n + O(log^2 n). - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Oct 23 2015

A004172.name: Triangle of coefficients of Euler polynomials E_2n(x) (exponents in increasing order).

A004173.name: Triangle of coefficients of Euler polynomials E_2n(x) (exponents in decreasing order).

A004174.name: Triangle of coefficients of Euler polynomials 2^n*E_n(x) (exponents in increasing order).

A004175.name: Triangle of coefficients of Euler polynomials 2^n*E_n(x) (exponents in decreasing order).

A004185.name: Arrange digits of n in increasing order, then (for n>0) omit the zeros.

A004186.name: Arrange digits of n in decreasing order.

A004187.name: a(n) = 7*a(n-1) - a(n-2) with a(0) = 0, a(1) = 1.
formula: a(n) = F(4*n)/3 = A033888(n)/3, where F=A000045 (the Fibonacci sequence).
a(n) = S(2*n-1, sqrt(9))/sqrt(9) = S(n-1, 7); S(n, x) := U(n, x/2), Chebyshev polynomials of the 2nd kind, A049310.
a(n) = sum(i=0..n-1, C(2*n-1-i, i)*5^(n-i-1) ). - Mario Catalani (mario.catalani(AT)unito.it), Jul 23 2004
Sum_{n >= 1} a(n)*x^(2*n) = -A(x)*A(-x), where A(x) = Sum_{n >= 1} Fibonacci(2*n)*x^n.
1 + Sum_{n >= 1} a(n)*x^(2*n) = H(x)*H(-x) = I(x)*I(-x), where H(x) = 1 + Sum_{n >= 1} Fibonacci(2*n + 3)*x^n and I(x) = 1 + x + x*Sum_{n >= 1} Fibonacci(2*n - 1)*x^n. (End)

A004188.name: a(n) = n*(3*n^2 - 1)/2.
formula: Partial sums of n-1 3-spaced triangular numbers, e.g., a(4) = t(1) + t(4) + t(7) = 1 + 10 + 28 = 39. - _Jon Perry_, Jul 23 2003
a(n) = C(2*n+1,3) + C(n+1,3), n >= 0. - _Zerinvary Lajos_, Jan 21 2007

A004189.name: a(n) = 10*a(n-1) - a(n-2); a(0) = 0, a(1) = 1.
formula: a(n) = S(2*n-1, sqrt(12))/sqrt(12) = S(n-1, 10); S(n, x) := U(n, x/2), Chebyshev polynomials of 2nd kind, A049310. S(-1, x) := 0.

A004190.name: Expansion of 1/(1 - 11*x + x^2).
formula: a(n) = S(2*n+1, sqrt(13))/sqrt(13) = S(n, 11); S(n, x) := U(n, x/2), Chebyshev polynomials of 2nd kind, A049310.
a(n) = -a(-2-n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 14 2018

A004191.name: Expansion of 1/(1 - 12*x + x^2).
formula: a(n) = S(n, 12) with S(n, x) := U(n, x/2) Chebyshev's polynomials of the second kind. See A049310.
a(n) = 12*a(n-1) - a(n-2) for n>1, a(0)=1, a(1)=12. - _Philippe Deléham_, Nov 17 2008
a(n) = b such that (-1)^(n+1)*Integral_{x=0..Pi/2} (sin((n+1)*x))/(6+cos(x)) dx = c + b*(log(2)+log(3)-log(7)). - _Francesco Daddi_, Aug 01 2011

A004192.name: Numbers obtained by reversing digits of factorial numbers.

A004194.name: Number of partitions of 1/n into 3 reciprocals of positive integers.

A004195.name: The numbers not expressible as the sum of 4 distinct nonzero squares can be written D*4^n union E. This is D.

A004196.name: The numbers not expressible as the sum of 4 distinct nonzero squares can be written D*4^n union E. This is E.

A004201.name: Accept one, reject one, accept two, reject two, ...
formula: a(n) = n + t(t+1)/2, where t = floor((-1+sqrt(8*n-7))/2). - _Boris Putievskiy_, Dec 13 2012

A004202.name: Skip 1, take 1, skip 2, take 2, skip 3, take 3, etc.
formula: T(n, k) = n^2 + k, for n>=1, k>=1 as a triangular array. a(n) = n + A127739(n). - _Michael Somos_, May 03 2019

A004203.name: Numbers n such that 54*10^n + 1 is prime.

A004204.name: Number of permutations of length n with spread 0.

A004205.name: Number of permutations of length n with spread 1.

A004206.name: Number of permutations of length n with spread 2.

A004207.name: a(0) = 1, a(n) = sum of digits of all previous terms.
formula: For n>1, a(n) = a(n-1) + sum of digits of a(n-1).
For n > 1: a(n) = A062028(a(n-1)). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Oct 14 2013

A004208.name: a(n) = n * (2*n - 1)!! - Sum_{k=0..n-1} a(k) * (2*n - 2*k - 1)!!.
formula: G.f.: ( 1/Q(0) -1 )/x where Q(k) = 1 - x*(2*k+1)/(1 - x*(2*k+4)/Q(k+1) ); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Mar 19 2013
G.f.: 2/x/G(0) - 1/x, where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - 2*x*(2*k+1)/(2*x*(2*k+1) - 1 + 2*x*(2*k+4)/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 31 2013
G.f.: 1/(2*x^2) -1/(2*x) - G(0)/(2*x^2), where G(k)= 1 - x*(k+1)/G(k+1) ; (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Aug 15 2013

A004209.name: For m=2,3,..., write m in bases m,m-1,...,3,2.

A004210.name: "Magic" integers: a(n+1) is the smallest integer m such that there is no overlap between the sets {m, m-a(i), m+a(i): 1 <= i <= n} and {a(i), a(i)-a(j), a(i)+a(j): 1 <= j < i <= n}.
formula: a(n+1) = min{ k | k and k +- a(i) are not equal to a(i) or a(i)-a(j) or a(i)+a(j) for any n+1 > i > j > 0}. [Corrected by _T. D. Noe_, Sep 08 2008]

A004211.name: Shifts one place left under 2nd-order binomial transform.
formula: E.g.f.: exp(sinh(x)*exp(x)) = exp(int(t=0..x, exp(2*t))) = exp((exp(2*x)-1)/2). - _Joerg Arndt_, Apr 30 2011 and May 13 2011
Stirling transform of A000085. - _Vladeta Jovovic_ May 14 2004
Define f_1(x), f_2(x), ... such that f_1(x)=e^x, f_{n+1}(x) = (d/dx)(x*f_n(x)), for n=2,3,.... Then a(n) = e^(-1/2)*2^{n-1}*f_n(1/2). - _Milan Janjic_, May 30 2008
a(n) = upper left term in M^n, M = an infinite square production matrix with an appended diagonal of (2,2,2,...) to the right of Pascal's triangle:
a(n) = D^n(exp(x)) evaluated at x = 0, where D is the operator (1+2*x)*d/dx. Cf. A000110. - _Peter Bala_, Nov 25 2011
G.f. A(x) satisfies A(x)=1+x/(1-2*x)*A(x/(1-2*x)), a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} binomial(n-1,k-1)*2^(n-k)*a(k-1), a(0)=1. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Nov 28 2011 [corrected by _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, May 02 2019]

Recurrence equation: a(n+1) = Sum_{k = 0..n} 2^(n-k)*C(n,k)*a(k). Written umbrally this is a(n+1) = (a+2)^n (expand the binomial and replace a^k with a(k)). More generally, a*f(a) = f(a+2) holds umbrally for any polynomial f(x). An inductive argument then establishes the umbral recurrence a*(a-2)*(a-4)*...*(a-2*(n-1)) = 1 with a(0) = 1. Compare with the Bell numbers B(n) = A000110(n), which satisfy the umbral recurrence B*(B-1)*...*(B-(n-1)) = 1 with B(0) = 1. Cf. A009235. Touchard's congruence holds for odd prime p: a(p+k) = (a(k) + a(k+1)) (mod p) for k = 0,1,2,... (adapt the proof of Theorem 10.1 in Gessel). In particular, a(p) = 2 (mod p) for odd prime p. - _Peter Bala_, May 16 2012

G.f.: (1/E(0)-1)/x  where E(k) = 1 - x/(1 + 2*x - 2*x*(k+1)/E(k+1)); (continued fraction, 2-step). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Sep 21 2012
G.f.: G(0)- 1/x where G(k) = 1 - (4*x*k-1)/(x - x^4/(x^3 - (4*x*k-1)*(4*x*k+2*x-1)*(4*x*k+4*x-1)/G(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jan 08 2013.

G.f.: 1/Q(0), where Q(k) = 1 - x/(1 - 2*x*(2*k+1)/( 1 - x/(1 - 4*x*(k+1)/Q(k+1) ))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Apr 15 2013

Compare with the Bell numbers B(n) = A000110(n), which satisfy the umbral recurrence B*(B-1)*...*(B-(n-1)) = 1 with B(0) = 1.

a(0) = a(1) = 0; for n>1, a(n) = n - 1 - floor(a(n-1)/2). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Nov 26 2002
a(n) = a(n-1) + (1/2)((-1)^floor((2*n+2)/3)+1), with a(0)=0. - Mario Catalani (mario.catalani(AT)unito.it), Oct 20 2003

A004524.name: Three even followed by one odd.
formula: If the sequence is extended to negative arguments in the natural way, it satisfies a(n) = -a(2-n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 19 2003

Euler transform of length 4 sequence [2, -1, 0, 1]. - _Michael Somos_, Apr 03 2017

A004525.name: One even followed by three odd.
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) - a(n-2) + a(n-3) + 1 = n - A004524(n+1). - _Henry Bottomley_, Mar 08 2000
a(n) = -a(-n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 19 2003
a(n) = floor(n/4) + ceiling(n/4). See also A004396, one even followed by two odd and A002620, quarter-squares: floor(n/2)*ceiling(n/2). - _Jonathan Vos Post_, Mar 19 2006
Euler transform of length 6 sequence [1, 0, 1, 1, 0, -1]. - _Michael Somos_, Apr 03 2017
a(n) = n-1-a(n-2) for n >= 2. - _Kritsada Moomuang_, 29 Oct 2019

A004526.name: Nonnegative integers repeated, floor(n/2).
formula: G.f.: 1/(1-x) * Sum_{k >= 0} t^2/(1-t^4) where t = x^2^k. - _Ralf Stephan_, Feb 24 2004
a(n) = (n-(1-(-1)^n)/2)/2 = 1/2*(n-|sin(n*Pi/2)|). Likewise: a(n) = (n-A000035(n))/2. Also: a(n) = Sum_{0<=k<=n, A000035(k)}. - _Hieronymus Fischer_, Jun 01 2007
The expression floor((x^2-1)/(2*x)) (x >= 1) produces this sequence. - _Mohammad K. Azarian_, Nov 08 2007; corrected by _M. F. Hasler_, Nov 17 2008
a(n+1) = A002620(n+1) - A002620(n) = floor((n+1)/2)*ceiling((n+1)/2) - floor(n^2/4). - _Jonathan Vos Post_, May 20 2010
For n >= 2, a(n) = floor(log_2(2^a(n-1)+2^a(n-2))). - _Vladimir Shevelev_, Jun 22 2010
Euler transform of length 2 sequence [ 1, 1]. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 03 2014

A004981.name: a(n) = (2^n/n!) * Product_{k=0..n-1} (4*k + 1).
formula: a(n) = (Sum_{m=1..n} m*Sum_{k=m..n} binomial(-m+2*k-1,k-1)*2^(n+m-k)*binomial(2*n-k-1,n-1))/n, n>0, a(0)=1. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Dec 26 2011
D-finite with recurrence: n*a(n) = 2*(4*n-3)*a(n-1). - _R. J. Mathar_, Mar 14 2014
E.g.f.: is the hypergeometric function of type 1F1, in Maple notation hypergeom([1/4], [1], 8*x).

Representation as n-th moment of a positive function on (0, 8): a(n)=int(x^n*(sqrt(2)/(16*Pi*(x/8)^(3/4)*(1-x/8)^(1/4))), x=0..8), n=0, 1, ... . This function is the solution of the Hausdorff moment problem on (0, 8) with moments equal to a(n). As a consequence this representation is unique. (End)

A004982.name: a(n) = (2^n/n!) * Product_{k=0..n-1} (4*k + 3).
formula: E.g.f.: is the hypergeometric function of type 1F1, in Maple notation hypergeom([3/4], [1], 8*x).

Representation as n-th moment of a positive function on (0, 8): a(n) = Integral_{x=0..8} ( x^n*(2^(1/4)/(8*Pi*x^(1/4)*(1-x/8)^(3/4)) ) dx, n >= 0. This function is the solution of the Hausdorff moment problem on (0, 8) with moments equal to a(n). As a consequence this representation is unique. (End)
D-finite with recurrence: n*a(n) +2*(-4*n+1)*a(n-1)=0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Jan 16 2020

A004983.name: a(n) = (2^n/n!) * Product_{k=0..n-1} (4*k - 3).

D-finite with recurrence: n*a(n) +2*(-4*n+7)*a(n-1)=0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Jan 16 2020

A004984.name: a(n) = (2^n/n!)*Product_{k=0..n-1} (4*k - 1).
formula: a(n) = -1/n*(if n=1 then (2)^n else Sum_{k=1..n-1} 2^n*binomial(k+n-1, n-1) * (Sum_{j=0..k} (binomial(k,j)*binomial(j,n-1-3*k+2*j)*(3/2)^(3*k-n+1-j)*(-1)^(n-1-3*k)*(1/4)^(k-j) ) ), n>0. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Sep 14 2010
D-finite with recurrence: n*a(n) +2*(-4*n+5)*a(n-1)=0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Jan 16 2020

A004987.name: a(n) = (3^n/n!)*Product_{k=0..n-1} (3*k + 1).
formula: Representation as n-th moment of a positive function on (0, 9): a(n) = Integral_{x=0..9} ( x^n*(1/(Pi*sqrt(3)*6*(x/9)^(2/3)*(1-x/9)^(1/3))) ), n >= 0. This function is the solution of the Hausdorff moment problem on (0, 9) with moments equal to a(n). As a consequence this representation is unique. - _Karol A. Penson_, Jan 30 2003
D-finite with recurrence: n*a(n) + 3*(2-3*n)*a(n-1)=0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Jun 07 2013
0 = a(n) * (81*a(n+1) - 15*a(n+2)) + a(n+1) * (-3*a(n+1) + a(n+2)) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Jan 27 2014
